snippet.textDisplay:
Third-party strategy guides have done overall more harm than good in this world. Final Fantasy XI players (yes, the first one that was an MMO; you can presumably already start to see the problem here) have either repressed memories of or suffer PTSD from the horrors of the dreaded Brady guide that some . . . we'll generously say "less-than-savvy" players seemed to treat as gospel. In a game that routinely required players to coordinate to get anything done, which in turn required them to know what they're doing, the mere existence Bradygames actively detracted from the playability of FFXI.


Furthermore, anybody who's even skimmed through a Prima Pokémon Strategy Guide can safely say "good riddance to bad rubbish;" in a game with hundreds of monsters to keep track of, the "not knowing what you're talking about" error rate becomes an easily calculable percentage.

snippet.textDisplay:
Walkthroughs used to be a work of art. I owned every Final Fantasy (and many other RPGs) strategy guide before I had even played them all. I had memorized every secret in Zelda, Mario 3, etc. I would take them to school and read them all day long. It resulted in me becoming a living walkthrough for how to beat just about any game my circle of friends were playing (this was before widespread access to the internet). It got to the point where I was hardly even playing games anymore, just reading about them. Everyone came to me for information about games.

Scott, you should have totally brought up Final Fantasy IX’s abysmal PlayOnline integration.

Edit: nevermind, you did bring it up, you sly fox.

snippet.textDisplay:
As the novel coronavirus is spreading fast and threatening the lives of millions of people around the globe, I’ve read stories about people infected with the virus making a full recovery by reciting “Falun Dafa is good; Truthfulness, Compassion, Forbearance is good.”

While I don’t know what the specific mechanism is behind the seemingly miraculous recoveries, I did remember some bacteria experiments that another Falun Dafa practitioner did in her microbiology classes.

The Two Blank Bacterial Culture Slides
Deyuan was born in Germany. She was introduced to Falun Dafa, an ancient spiritual discipline, by her parents in 1997. She is currently studying at a medical school in Germany.

Deyuan said that, in her first microbiology class in college a few years ago, each student was given a few agar slides and asked to put their fingers on the plate to see what bacteria were on their hands. After a few days of culturing in the incubator, most of her classmates’ slides had some bacterial colonies growing on them. But Deyuan’s slide was blank.

She was puzzled, “I didn’t remember washing my hands before the class. But why didn’t anything growing on it?”

During the next class, the teacher asked them to test the bacteria on the surface of an object. This time, Deyuan went with a piece of a banknote, which is known to have many microorganisms on it. But to her surprise, her experiment “failed” again – nothing grew on the slide.

snippet.textDisplay: Having strategy guides was the shit before I had a PC in my pocket. I remember carrying my golden sun or pokemon strat guide everywhere with me so I wouldn't ever be caught off guard. It was handy for games like that with sheets detailing values, drop rates, etc. Especially when games wouldn't get patched, just released as is. and as you mentioned the best part about them was the full color pages and the art decorating the pages. Now as an artist I definitely do buy "art of" books but really i wouldn't mind buying a strategy guide if that's the closest thing I could get.
snippet.textOriginal: Having strategy guides was the shit before I had a PC in my pocket. I remember carrying my golden sun or pokemon strat guide everywhere with me so I wouldn't ever be caught off guard.
